{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The speech-to-text output preserves speaker labels so that the summary can attribute statements to specific attendees.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The main failure boundary is local handoff/parsing between transcription response handling and summarization input formatting. A unit test can miss schema-mapping bugs across modules, but real network/model variability is not strictly required to catch this class of failure.","test_description":"Run an end-to-end local wiring test (transcription adapter -> transcript normalizer -> summarization prompt builder) using a realistic STT payload fixture with multiple speaker turns and label formats. Assert speaker IDs/names are preserved in the intermediate transcript and appear in attribution-ready structured input.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The structured summary contains at least one action item for every attendee who was assigned a task during the meeting.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This is a content-quality requirement on LLM extraction/completeness, not just wiring. Deterministic mocks can hide real misses where the model omits an attendee’s task assignment.","test_description":"Use a real LLM call on transcripts containing explicit per-attendee assignments. Validate output schema and check recall: each attendee with an assigned task in the transcript has at least one corresponding action item in the summary.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Key decisions mentioned in the transcript appear in the \"decisions\" section of the summary, not buried in the narrative.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on model judgment about salience and section placement. Mocked outputs would likely always satisfy placement and miss real misclassification/formatting drift.","test_description":"Send real meeting transcripts with clearly stated decisions to the production-like summarization prompt/model. Assert each expected decision is present in the dedicated `decisions` field/section and not only in freeform narrative text.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.15}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the audio file is longer than 60 minutes, the service splits it into segments and processes them sequentially, merging the results into a single coherent summary.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This spans multiple sequential AI-backed steps (segment transcription + per-segment/merged summarization) where cross-step context loss and merge quality failures emerge only in chained execution.","test_description":"Execute the long-audio path with a real >60-minute recording, forcing segmentation. Run full sequential processing across segments and final merge, then verify: segment ordering preserved, no dropped segment content, and final summary remains globally coherent with consolidated action items/decisions across segment boundaries.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.2,"Workflow":0.45}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full pipeline — upload audio, transcribe, summarize, deliver structured output — completes without manual intervention for a real meeting recording.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This is explicitly a full agent pipeline acceptance behavior with multiple external/agentic stages in sequence. Lower levels cannot reveal end-to-end orchestration and cross-stage failure modes.","test_description":"Run a production-like end-to-end test using a real meeti